getNewVariantWithSpecifiedValue

public ITrait<T> getNewVariantWithSpecifiedValue(T val)
Description copied from interface: ITraitDimension
Returns a new ITrait with the specified value. This cannot be included in the ITraitFactory interface because that interface is not a generic and does not expose the underlying type. So we do it here. Often this will not be used in models, but in validation and verification tests.

getRandomTraitFromDimension

public ITrait<T> getRandomTraitFromDimension()
Returns a random trait from the dimension. CAUTION: This returns ANY trait in the dimension, even one which has a zero adoption count. It is useful for initializing a population, or when you want innovation to "resurrect" extinct traits. But it should not be used to select a *current* trait randomly with a non-zero adoption count.

Specified by:
getRandomTraitFromDimension in interface ITraitDimension<T>

getNewVariantBasedUponExistingVariant

public ITrait getNewVariantBasedUponExistingVariant(ITrait existingTrait)
Description copied from interface: ITraitFactory
For variation models in which new variants can be created with reference to an existing trait (e.g., perceptual copying error), this constructs a new trait based upon the existing trait passed in. The implementation of this is up to the specific variation model.
